result.execSummary:
The defendant Jeffrey T. Jordan was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Misdemeanor Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Jeffrey T. Jordan

records.addlTxt: Return on warrant on August 18, 2022 at 09:30 am.
Reminder Notice indicating amount due mailed to defendant.

(Case called at 10:23 AM) Prosecuting attorney Robert W. Stoiber appeared in court for the State of Wisconsin, Defendant Jeffrey T. Jordan appeared in court, Attorney Alicia Linzmeier appeared in court for Jeffrey T. Jordan. 
Defense indicates there is an agreement- recites the joint sentence recommendation. Defense requests 41 days jail credit from probation hold- notes court of appeals case. State requests to look into the jail credit during the colloquy by the Court. Defendant pleads No Contest to Count 2- Misdemeanor Battery as Domestic Abuse. Defendant is advised of charges, maximum penalties, elements of the crime(s) and constitutional rights. Court accepts plea and finds the Defendant guilty. Remaining charges are dismissed and read in. 
Court withhold sentence and orders 18 months Probation with the following conditions: No contact with J.K., unless approved by the agent and J.K.; Maintain absolute sobriety; Provide DNA sample and pay surcharge; Court costs. 
Defense makes argument for credit from Probation hold. State indicates the 41 days credit was ordered in his revocation case yesterday- makes argument against 41 days credit. 
Court orders no credit, if revoked.
